completion.content:
To add error handling to your fetch request, you can use `.catch()` or try-catch blocks to catch any potential errors. Here's how you can modify your code using `try-catch`:

```javascript
import { createAsyncThunk } from '@reduxjs/toolkit';

export const loadBackgroundImage = createAsyncThunk(
  "backgroundImage/fetchBackgroundImage",
  async (thunkAPI) => {
    try {
      const data = await fetch(unsplashEndpoint);

      if (!data.ok) {
        throw new Error(`Error fetching data: ${data.status}`);
      }

      const jsonData = await data.json();
      return jsonData;
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Error in fetch request:', error.message);
      return thunkAPI.rejectWithValue(error.message);
    }
  }
);
```

In the example above, the fetch request is wrapped inside a `try` block. If any error is encountered while fetching or parsing the data, it will be caught in the `catch` block. The error message is logged to the console, and `rejectWithValue` is used to pass the error message back to the Redux store, allowing you to handle the error in your reducers or display a user-friendly error message.

Make sure to import `createAsyncThunk` from `@reduxjs/toolkit`, and replace `unsplashEndpoint` with the actual endpoint you are using.

