Developing environmentally friendly solutions using Java or any other programming language depends on the context and purpose of your projects. In order to give you a concrete idea on how Java can be used to achieve these goals, I'll provide a simple example: You can create a platform that encourages businesses to track and reduce their emissions. Java can be used to develop the backend of such a platform.

Here's a code snippet illustrating an EmissionsTracker class that calculates the reductions required:

```java
public class EmissionsTracker {
    private double currentGreenhouseGases;
    private double currentNitrogenOxides;
    private double currentVolatileOrganicCompounds;

    public EmissionsTracker(double greenhouseGases, double nitrogenOxides, double volatileOrganicCompounds) {
        this.currentGreenhouseGases = greenhouseGases;
        this.currentNitrogenOxides = nitrogenOxides;
        this.currentVolatileOrganicCompounds = volatileOrganicCompounds;
    }

    public double getReductionTarget(double currentEmission, double reductionRate) {
        return currentEmission * reductionRate;
    }

    public void calculateReductions() {
        double reductionRate = 0.25;
        double targetGreenhouseGases = getReductionTarget(currentGreenhouseGases, reductionRate);
        double targetNitrogenOxides = getReductionTarget(currentNitrogenOxides, reductionRate);
        double targetVolatileOrganicCompounds = getReductionTarget(currentVolatileOrganicCompounds, reductionRate);

        System.out.println("Greenhouse Gases reduction target: " + targetGreenhouseGases);
        System.out.println("Nitrogen Oxides reduction target: " + targetNitrogenOxides);
        System.out.println("Volatile Organic Compounds reduction target: " + targetVolatileOrganicCompounds);
    }
}
```

You can then use this EmissionsTracker class to set emission reduction targets for businesses.

