Creating a script to show the weather requires fetching data from a weather API to get accurate and updated information. In this example, I'll use the free OpenWeatherMap API. First, you'll need to sign up for an API key at https://openweathermap.org/api.

Once you have an API key, you can follow the steps below.

1. Create a new Console Application in C#.

2. Install the `Newtonsoft.Json` package via NuGet Package Manager to parse the JSON response from the API.

3. Replace the content of your `Program.cs` with the following code:

```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Net;
using System.Text;
using Newtonsoft.Json;

namespace WeatherApp
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Enter the city name (e.g., 'New York'):");
            string city = Console.ReadLine();

            ShowWeather(city);

            Console.WriteLine("\nPress any key to exit...");
            Console.ReadKey(true);
        }

        static void ShowWeather(string city)
        {
            string apiKey = "YOUR_API_KEY";
            string requestUrl = $"https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather?q={city}&appid={apiKey}&units=metric";

            try
            {
                HttpWebRequest request = (HttpWebRequest)WebRequest.Create(requestUrl);
                HttpWebResponse response = (HttpWebResponse)request.GetResponse();
                StreamReader reader = new StreamReader(response.GetResponseStream(), Encoding.UTF8);
                string jsonResponse = reader.ReadToEnd();

                dynamic weatherData = JsonConvert.DeserializeObject(jsonResponse);

                Console.WriteLine("\nWeather data for " + city + ":");
                Console.WriteLine("Temperature: " + weatherData.main.temp + "°C");
                Console.WriteLine("Humidity: " + weatherData.main.humidity + "%");
                Console.WriteLine("Weather: " + weatherData.weather[0].description);
            }
            catch (WebException ex)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Error: Unable to fetch data. Please check the city name and your API key.");
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Replace `YOUR_API_KEY` with the API key you received from OpenWeatherMap.

4. Run the application! The user will be prompted to enter a city name, and the script will fetch and display the weather data for that city.

Keep in mind that the OpenWeatherMap API has some rate limits, so if you plan to use this in a production environment or make many requests, consider upgrading your API plan or implementing some caching strategies.

