JavaScript mein Promise, asynchronous programming ke liye ek object hai jo aane wali value ya error ko represent karta hai. Yeh single value ya operation ka result ko future mein return karta hai. Promise object successful execution ke liye "resolve" aur error ke liye "reject" status hota hai.

Aap ne kisi action ka result future mein lena ho tou Promise ka use kar sakte hain. Niche, main aap ko ek simple Promise example dikha raha hoon:

```javascript
// ek Promise banate hain 
const promiseExample = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const num = Math.random();
    if (num < 0.5) {
        resolve("Kamyaabi! Number 0.5 se kam hai: " + num);
    } else {
        reject("Nakaami! Number 0.5 se zyada hai: " + num);
    }
});

// Promise ka result hasil karne ke liye .then aur .catch statements use hote hain
promiseExample
    .then((successMessage) => {
        console.log(successMessage);
    })
    .catch((failureMessage) => {
        console.log(failureMessage);
    });
```

Is example mein, humne ek `promiseExample` naam ka Promise banaya hai. Iss Promise mein ek random number generate hota hai, aur agar wo number 0.5 se kam hota hai, to Promise "resolve" ho jata hai aur kamyaabi ka message print hota hai. Agar number 0.5 se zyada hota hai, to Promise "reject" ho jata hai aur nakaami ka message print hota hai.

