You can achieve this by splitting the input text into chunks and then mapping them to render inside `<div>` tags. Here's an example of how you can do this in a functional React component:

First, let's create a helper function that splits the input text into chunks of 280 characters or less:

```javascript
function splitText(text, maxLength = 280) {
  const chunks = [];
  let startIndex = 0;
  while (startIndex < text.length) {
    const endIndex = startIndex + maxLength;
    chunks.push(text.slice(startIndex, endIndex));
    startIndex = endIndex;
  }
  return chunks;
}
```

Now, here's a sample React component that demonstrates how to use this function in conjunction with a textarea input:

```javascript
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const App = () => {
  const [inputText, setInputText] = useState('');

  const handleChange = (event) => {
    setInputText(event.target.value);
  };

  const chunks = splitText(inputText);

  return (
    <div>
      <textarea
        value={inputText}
        onChange={handleChange}
        rows={5}
        placeholder="Enter text"
      />

      {chunks.map((chunk, index) => (
        <div key={index} style={{ border: '1px solid #ccc', margin: '8px 0' }}>
          <p>
            <strong>Part {index + 1}:</strong>
          </p>
          <p>{chunk}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this example, we use the `useState` hook to manage the contents of the textarea input. The `handleChange` function updates the input text value whenever it changes. The `chunks` constant receives an array of text chunks created by the `splitText` function, and we map over this array to render it within `<div>` tags.

Finally, you can customize the styling of each div block as you prefer. We have added a simple border and margin to differentiate between the text chunks in this example.

